  "text": "The Kubernetes scheduler plugin framework architecture is implemented across several key files that work together to orchestrate the scheduling cycle for pods:\n\n## Framework Interfaces (pkg/scheduler/framework/interface.go)\n\nThe framework defines a set of plugin interfaces that extend the base Plugin interface. These interfaces represent different extension points in the scheduling cycle:\n\n1. **Pre-Scheduling Phase**: PreEnqueuePlugin (called before adding pods to the queue) and QueueSortPlugin (sorts pods in the queue)\n\n2. **Filtering Phase**: PreFilterPlugin (initial pod processing), FilterPlugin (node feasibility checks), and PostFilterPlugin (runs after filtering fails, typically for preemption)\n\n3. **Scoring Phase**: PreScorePlugin (informational), ScorePlugin (ranks feasible nodes), and ScoreExtensions (normalizes scores)\n\n4. **Reservation Phase**: ReservePlugin (updates plugin state when scheduling decisions are made)\n\n5. **Binding Phase**: PreBindPlugin (pre-binding checks), PermitPlugin (allows/delays binding), BindPlugin (actual binding), and PostBindPlugin (post-binding cleanup)\n\nThe Framework interface itself (line 686) is the main abstraction that plugins use through the Handle interface, which provides access to the scheduler's data structures and methods to run other plugins.\n\n## Framework Implementation (pkg/scheduler/framework/runtime/framework.go)\n\nThe frameworkImpl struct (line 52) is the concrete runtime implementation of the Framework interface. It maintains lists of all registered plugins at each extension point and provides methods to invoke them:\n\n- RunPreFilterPlugins (line 709) - runs PreFilter plugins and can filter nodes\n- RunFilterPlugins (line 872) - runs Filter plugins to check node feasibility\n- RunPostFilterPlugins (line 919) - runs PostFilter plugins for recovery\n- RunPreScorePlugins (line 1063) - runs PreScore plugins\n- RunScorePlugins (line 1112) - runs Score plugins and returns node rankings\n- RunReservePluginsReserve (line 1370) - runs Reserve plugins to update state\n- RunPermitPlugins (line 1454) - runs Permit plugins to allow/delay binding\n- RunPreBindPlugins (line 1243) - runs PreBind plugins\n- RunBindPlugins (line 1286) - runs Bind plugins to bind the pod to a node\n- RunPostBindPlugins (line 1335) - runs PostBind plugins for cleanup\n\nThe frameworkImpl also has RunPreFilterExtensionAddPod and RunPreFilterExtensionRemovePod methods (lines 781, 826) for incremental updates.\n\n## Plugin Registry (pkg/scheduler/framework/plugins/registry.go)\n\nThe NewInTreeRegistry function (line 47) builds a registry with all built-in plugins. The Registry type is defined in pkg/scheduler/framework/runtime/registry.go (line 71) as a map from plugin name to PluginFactory. The registry includes plugins like:\n- NodeAffinity, PodTopologySpread, TaintToleration\n- NodeName, NodePorts, NodeResources\n- ImageLocality, InterPodAffinity\n- VolumeBinding, VolumeRestrictions, VolumeZone\n- DefaultBinder, DefaultPreemption, SchedulingGates\n- DynamicResources, QueueSort\n\n## Scheduler and Orchestration (pkg/scheduler/scheduler.go and pkg/scheduler/schedule_one.go)\n\nThe Scheduler struct (line 66 in scheduler.go) is the main scheduler controller. Its Run method (line 464) starts the scheduler and runs the scheduling loop continuously.\n\nThe ScheduleOne method (line 65 in schedule_one.go) orchestrates the complete scheduling cycle for a single pod:\n\n1. Retrieves the next pod to schedule from the queue\n2. Selects the appropriate framework profile for the pod\n3. Creates a CycleState to store per-pod state during scheduling\n4. Calls the schedulingCycle function which:\n   - Calls SchedulePod with the framework\n   - This triggers the plugin execution chain through the frameworkImpl\n   - Returns a ScheduleResult if successful\n5. If scheduling succeeds, asynchronously executes bindingCycle to:\n   - Run PreBind, Permit, Bind, and PostBind plugins\n   - Bind the pod to the selected node\n\nThe flow is: Run() → ScheduleOne() → frameworkImpl.Run*Plugins() → individual plugin implementations.\n\n## Data Structures (pkg/scheduler/framework/types.go)\n\nKey data structures used throughout include:\n- NodeInfo: Contains node metadata, pods on the node, and allocatable resources\n- PodInfo: Wrapper around a Pod object with additional metadata\n- CycleState: Stores per-pod state during a scheduling cycle, allowing plugins to share information\n- Status: Return value from plugins indicating success/failure with reasons\n\nThis architecture allows plugins to be added at various extension points without modifying the core scheduler logic, making it highly extensible."
}

